initial_story: the aim of this paper is to provide a classification of multilingual andplurilingual electronic lexicographic resources which would enable, one the onehand, the implementation of quantitative and qualitative criteria to produce atypological taxonomy of lexicographical tools, such as dictionaries, as opposedto platforms and websites and, on the other, the distinction of multilingualand plurilingual resources in terms of their larger or lesser prototypingdegree. in addition to offering a thorough description of the differentresources, this paper also puts forward some parameters and typologicalproposals to define and demarcate a number of electronic resources,particularly multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also outlining, andeven questioning, the object of study of multilingual and plurilinguallexicography.
stories: Specifically, this proposed typology aims to establish a framework for classifying multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources, such as dictionaries, thesauruses, and lexical databases, based on their characteristics, functionality, and coverage, thereby facilitating the organization, searching, and evaluation of these resources, as well as enabling the identification of gaps and overlaps in the existing inventory of electronic lexicographic tools, ultimately leading to a better understanding of the nature and scope of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

Additionally, the typology will investigate the role of ontology and semantic networks in facilitating semantic search and retrieval of entries across different lexicographic resources, and explore the challenges and opportunities of aligning heterogeneous schema and formatting conventions, thus providing a solid basis for the development of a standardized lexicographic reference system, enabling the harmonization of data and ensuring the scalability and maintainability of the classification framework over time.

In order to address these issues, the study will leverage the strengths of recent advances in natural language processing and information retrieval, incorporating techniques such as weighted latent Dirichlet allocation and non-nonautical text classification. Furthermore, the development of a semantically-enriched thesaurus and a web-based interface will allow end-users to efficiently contribute to and disseminate lexicographic data, thus fostering collaboration and community engagement.

This will also be achieved through the deployment of machine learning algorithms, specifically neural networks, to analyze and extract relevant features from user-generated content, as well as the use of sentiment analysis and Named Entity Recognition techniques to identify patterns and trends in language use.
